[
    {
        "content": "<p>I've come across pro C* algebras, which are (it seems to me) essentially C* algebras where the underlying space is only a locally convex space instead of a Banach space: <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/pro-C-star-algebra\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/pro-C-star-algebra</a> (that is of course not the definition the nlab gives)</p>\n<p>Does anyone know if there is a category of topological spaces that is equivalent to the dual of the category of pro C* algebras?</p>",
        "id": 339430995,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677872673
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You mean commutative pro C*-algebras, of course.</p>",
        "id": 339432107,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873069
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know!  But we can figure out something pretty easily.</p>",
        "id": 339432148,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873086
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The category of commutative C*-algebras is equivalent to the opposite of the category of locally compact Hausdorff spaces.</p>",
        "id": 339432283,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873125
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/pro-objects\">[[pro-objects]]</a> in any category correspond to <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/ind-objects\">[[ind-objects]]</a> in the opposite category - this is just formal nonsense, like how limits in a category are colimits in the opposite category.  Pro-objects are \"imaginary, ideal limits\" of cofiltered diagrams in a category, and ind-objects are \"imaginary, ideal colimits\" of filtered diagrams in a category.</p>",
        "id": 339432664,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873268
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, commutative pro-C <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^\\ast</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> -algebras, or more precisely pro-(commutative C*-algebras) (which may well be the same thing) correspond to ind-(locally compact Hausdorff spaces).</p>",
        "id": 339432949,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873383
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So my answer is this question: what are ind-objects in the category locally compact Hausdorff spaces like?</p>",
        "id": 339433382,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873563
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>More hand-wavily: what sort of big spaces could we do by taking formal cofiltered colimits, or \"increasing unions\", of locally compact Hausdorff spaces?</p>",
        "id": 339433666,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873638
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example how about </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>↪</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>↪</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>↪</mo><mo>⋯</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathbb{R} \\hookrightarrow \\mathbb{R}^2 \\hookrightarrow \\mathbb{R}^3 \\hookrightarrow \\cdots </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6999em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8251em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8251em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.313em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">⋯</span></span></span></span> ?</p>",
        "id": 339433855,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873701
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In Top the colimit of this is called <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}^\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and it's not locally compact.</p>",
        "id": 339433966,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873726
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But it might be a fine ind-object in the locally compact Hausdorff spaces!</p>",
        "id": 339434042,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873753
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One has to be careful because the morphisms of these ind-objects might be quite different from morphisms in Top (= continuous maps).</p>",
        "id": 339434133,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677873799
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/281848-theory.3A-analysis/topic/Generalizations.20of.20C*.20algebras/near/339432283\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The category of commutative C*-algebras is equivalent to the opposite of the category of locally compact Hausdorff spaces.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I learned today that this is not true in the way I thought it was true!! <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/170984/are-commutative-c-algebras-really-dual-to-locally-compact-hausdorff-spaces\">https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/170984/are-commutative-c-algebras-really-dual-to-locally-compact-hausdorff-spaces</a></p>",
        "id": 339434602,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677873969
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But OK, this makes sense. I'll have to think more about what this means and learn more about pro and ind objects.</p>",
        "id": 339434805,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874044
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, okay!  I just naively extrapolated from the unital case.</p>",
        "id": 339434811,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874048
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Are there other examples of pro and ind objects that you know of?</p>",
        "id": 339434862,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874072
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I only learned about that today too.</p>",
        "id": 339434877,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Profinite groups are super important in Galois theory.</p>",
        "id": 339434943,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874090
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Now I seem to remember David Jaz Myers going on about profinite sets in homotopy type theory...</p>",
        "id": 339435057,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874136
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are many uses of pro-objects, but if you want something \"established\" think about how things like the absolute Galois group of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Q}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span></span></span></span> is best treated as a profinite group, not just a bare group.</p>",
        "id": 339435259,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874206
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What is the absolute Galois group?</p>",
        "id": 339435357,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874253
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Forget it.   <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span></p>",
        "id": 339435402,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874268
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK :)</p>",
        "id": 339435413,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874274
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's just like the most mysterious object in math, the group that has driven people insane... it's the Galois group of the algebraic numbers over the rational numbers.</p>",
        "id": 339435601,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874335
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, because each extension by adding an extra root is a finite extension</p>",
        "id": 339435701,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right.</p>",
        "id": 339435819,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So the whole group is a filtered colimit of all of those Galois groups which come from adding a finite number of roots.</p>",
        "id": 339435892,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874444
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Neat!</p>",
        "id": 339435918,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874451
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I get the problem now:</p>\n<p>It makes sense that to prove Gelfand-Naimark duality for nonunital C*-algebras people would adjoin a unit and reduce it to the unital case.  But then one is treating locally compact Hausdorff spaces as pointed compact Hausdorff spaces with the specified point (called \"infinity\") removed, and the maps are really basepoint-preserving maps between those pointed spaces!   Which are, alas, not the same as arbitrary continous maps between  locally compact Hausdorff spaces.  They're maps that do something rather simple at infinity.</p>",
        "id": 339436304,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874593
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right!</p>",
        "id": 339436518,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874688
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think those are called \"proper\" maps or something</p>",
        "id": 339436624,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874735
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"280755\">Owen Lynch</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/281848-theory.3A-analysis/topic/Generalizations.20of.20C*.20algebras/near/339435892\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>So the whole group is a filtered colimit of all of those Galois groups which come from adding a finite number of roots.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I agreed with this at first but it's not right.   It's a filtered <em>limit</em> of those finite Galois groups.</p>",
        "id": 339436653,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874745
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK, I mixed up pro and ind; pro is for limits?</p>",
        "id": 339436701,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874775
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, right, because <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}^{\\infty}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a colimit</p>",
        "id": 339436757,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874802
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK, that's how I'll remember this</p>",
        "id": 339436803,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677874810
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes.  </p>\n<p>If you have field extensions F <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊂</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\subset</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span></span></span></span> F' <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊂</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\subset</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span></span></span></span> F'' then the Galois group of F' over F is a <em>quotient</em> of the Galois group of F'' over F' not a subgroup.</p>",
        "id": 339436804,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874810
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually I guess this is just true for Galois extensions.</p>",
        "id": 339436946,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, the example of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}^\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is easier for us geometrically minded folks.</p>",
        "id": 339437087,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677874950
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Huh, I learned Galois theory before I learned algebraic geometry, so I didn't think about it this way at the time, but I wonder if you can think of Galois theory as another algebra/geometry duality, where the groups are the geometry half</p>",
        "id": 339437183,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677875011
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's a duality right but I don't want to answer your \"wonder\".</p>",
        "id": 339437288,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677875052
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wise :)</p>",
        "id": 339437336,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677875073
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's a readable short explanation of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galois_group#Infinite_groups\">Galois groups as profinite groups</a>.</p>",
        "id": 339437350,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677875080
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But it's actually confusing where it says</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>For example, the field extensions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msqrt><mi>a</mi></msqrt><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi></mstyle></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> {\\displaystyle \\mathbb {Q} ({\\sqrt {a}})/\\mathbb {Q} }</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0992em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord sqrt\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8492em;\"><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\" style=\"padding-left:0.833em;\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.8092em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"min-width:0.853em;height:1.08em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='1.08em' viewBox='0 0 400000 1080' preserveAspectRatio='xMinYMin slice'><path d='M95,702\nc-2.7,0,-7.17,-2.7,-13.5,-8c-5.8,-5.3,-9.5,-10,-9.5,-14\nc0,-2,0.3,-3.3,1,-4c1.3,-2.7,23.83,-20.7,67.5,-54\nc44.2,-33.3,65.8,-50.3,66.5,-51c1.3,-1.3,3,-2,5,-2c4.7,0,8.7,3.3,12,10\ns173,378,173,378c0.7,0,35.3,-71,104,-213c68.7,-142,137.5,-285,206.5,-429\nc69,-144,104.5,-217.7,106.5,-221\nl0 -0\nc5.3,-9.3,12,-14,20,-14\nH400000v40H845.2724\ns-225.272,467,-225.272,467s-235,486,-235,486c-2.7,4.7,-9,7,-19,7\nc-6,0,-10,-1,-12,-3s-194,-422,-194,-422s-65,47,-65,47z\nM834 80h400000v40h-400000z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1908em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span></span></span></span></span> for a square-free element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>a</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi></mstyle></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle a\\in \\mathbb {Q} }</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span></span></span></span></span> each have a unique degree 2 automorphism, inducing an automorphism in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Aut</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mstyle></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> {\\displaystyle \\operatorname {Aut} (\\mathbb {C} /\\mathbb {Q} )}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Aut</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></span> </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>because this makes it sound like the big Galois group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Aut</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mstyle></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> {\\displaystyle \\operatorname {Aut} (\\mathbb {C} /\\mathbb {Q} )}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Aut</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></span>  is a union, or colimit, of the smaller Galois groups!</p>",
        "id": 339437678,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677875200
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, that seems like an injection!</p>",
        "id": 339437847,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677875276
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK, neat; now it's back to the functional analysis grindstone for me :)</p>",
        "id": 339438068,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677875354
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You should be studying algebraic geometry and number theory now that I'm thinking about that.   <span aria-label=\"goofy\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f92a\" role=\"img\" title=\"goofy\">:goofy:</span></p>",
        "id": 339438487,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677875513
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When you come to Topos, I'll try and nerd snipe you back into analysis :)</p>",
        "id": 339441122,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1677876529
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I still like analysis.   I'm not sure I call pro-objects in the category of C* algebras \"analysis\", it reminds me of a category theorist's idea of what analysis <em>should</em> be about.   <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span>  But I like that too.</p>",
        "id": 339441615,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677876738
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It occurs to me that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}^\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is not just an ind-(locally compact Hausdorff space), but also an ind-(compact Hausdorff space). For example, it is the union of the subsets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi>N</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mi>N</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-N, N]^N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0913em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 339605394,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1677958910
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When you say \"pro-C*-algebra\", is it implicitly assumed that the maps in the pro-system are of some specific kind, say quotients by closed ideals?</p>",
        "id": 339605441,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1677958949
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It looks to me like section 2 of the first paper linked on the nlab page on pro-C*-algebras answers your question</p>",
        "id": 339606366,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1677959572
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm trying to find what's you're talking about in Amini's paper and I found this typo, clearly the result of injudicious global search and replace:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There are dif and only iferent topologies on...</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 339613467,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677964985
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I didn't find the answer to the question \"what sort of spaces correspond to pro-C*-algebras?\" in Amini's paper.  Maybe you meant some other paper?</p>",
        "id": 339613876,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677965363
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What's the answer?</p>",
        "id": 339613892,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677965378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh sorry, I meant the paper by N. C. Phillips in the first bullet point</p>",
        "id": 339614644,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1677966053
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The link in that paragraph could be easy to overlook.</p>",
        "id": 339614657,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1677966066
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The answer is, if I'm not mistaken, the category of \"compactological spaces\", which today are maybe better known as quasiseparated condensed sets. They are also the filtered colimits of compact Hausdorff spaces with injective transition maps.</p>",
        "id": 339614749,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1677966142
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, thanks!   I didn't see there was a link in there.</p>\n<p>I think you just satisfied my curiosity, at least for now.</p>",
        "id": 339616838,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677967907
    }
]